            },
            "answer_text": "Oil is a global market. The U.S. government does not steal or buy oil from the Middle East. The government buys finished products, lubricating oil, jet fuel, etc through contracts. The U.S. government does not own or operate any refineries anywhere in the world. The U.S. Government does not own any tankers or railroads to ship the oil from one place to another. Oil is traded for money (in U.S. Dollars) by traders located world wide that usually never even see the oil that they are buying and selling. That oil is shipped via tankers, pipelines, rail cars, and trucks to wherever the oil trader may make a profitable sale, less shipping costs which are paid to the shipping company(owners of the tankers, pipelines, rail cars, and trucks). It is not at all unusual for oil to be traded multiple times from the time it is produced until it arrives at a refinery. What the U.S. government does, via it\u2019s military reach, is to ensure that those global markets remain stable and do not fluctuate wildly in the event of some terror attack on a tanker, oil field, or refinery. To wit, President Trump authorized oil to be drawn from the strategic petroleum reserve \u201cif needed\u201d to calm jittery oil markets in the wake of the attack on the Saudi Refinery. This immediately settled the markets and it soon became clear that no long term shortage would occur. No oil was withdrawn for this purpose, just saying it would be was enough. The Strategic Petroleum reserve does make occasional trades in it\u2019s oil holdings due to the interference of Congress in laws they pass. The theory Congress operates on seems to be \u201cBuy High and Sell Low\u201d. So the U.S. Government\u2019s role is not to \u201csteal\u201d any country\u2019s oil. It is however, through it\u2019s military presence, restricting some sales from the market (Iran) and has a role in determining the ownership and profits of some oilfields such as the one in Syria by not allowing Assad access to what was once one of his major profit centers before it fell into ISIS control. ",
