                "href": "/profile/Bruce-A-McIntyre"
            },
            "answer_text": "The oil in the Middle East, produced by the OPEC nations, are sold on the open market. The US buys a fair amount of that oil, and pays market prices. While the US is a net exporter of Petroleum products, it also buys on the open market looking for delivery to certain ports, and for certain grades of petroleum. While there are those that state that the US should go into the MIddle East and steal oil, the reality is that historically, all the US has wanted is continued guaranteed access to buy the oil at market prices. In order to achieve this, the US has worked with nations in the Middle East to make that happen. Even the invasion of Iraq, which truly was significantly about oil, was about access to that oil. The multi-national oil companies (not the US government) wanted to be able to develop and extract the resource. But it was never about \u201cstealing.\u201d ",
